The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, June 17, 2004 				 Woman, health amp; workplace
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Womens health is the lowest priority for low-income families, cervical cancer is the second-most common cancer in developing countries, and lack of ante-natal care is the primary cause of a mothers death during labour. 																								These and other startling facts were thrown up for discussion at a seminar on working and occupational health in the city on Wednesday.																								Organised by NGO Stree Shakti at the Indian Institute of Social Welfare and Business Management, the seminar was one of the six regional workshops being held in India, to raise issues about work and womens health, in preparation for the IV International Congress of Women, Work and Health.																								To be held in November 2005 in New Delhi, it will highlight topics like health and environment for working women. Representatives from several NGOs and organisations present at the first-of-its-kind seminar in Calcutta discussed the health problems of women in menial occupations, from factory labourers to domestic workers.																								Presentations of studies by researchers at the Indian Statistical Institute  from reproductive health to cervical cancer  raised several points for discussion and topics for presentation at next years congress.
